class:: RubberBandPS
summary:: Formant preserving pitch shifter using the RubberBand library
related:: Classes/PitchShift
categories:: Libraries>FlexUGens, UGens>Filters>Pitch

Description::

RubberBandPS is a high-quality formant preserving pitch shifter using the RubberBand library.
Due to the nature of its implementation, there is some latency. The authors of the plugin say,
"Using RubberBandLiveShifter also gives a shorter processing delay than a typical buffering setup 
using RubberBandStretcher, making it a useful choice for some streamed or live situations. However, 
it is still not a low-latency effect, with a delay of 50ms or more between input and output signals 
depending on configuration." (link::https://github.com/breakfastquay/rubberband/blob/default/src/RubberBandLiveShifter.cpp::) 
The delay is noticeable if you are playing things with percussive onsets. 
It is not always a deal-breaker--you probably won't have trouble if you're harmonizing a bowed 
vibraphone, for example. Also, if you are using the original non-pitch-shifted sound along with 
the pitch-shifted sound, you can throw a short delay into the signal chain to synchronize the two 
(and tune the delay time by ear). See one of the code examples below for an illustration of the delay time.

For more information about the RubberBand library, visit link::https://breakfastquay.com/rubberband/::.

::note
This UGen uses quite a bit of CPU resources, which could be a problem on a less powerful computer.
You should also consider increasing the strong::memSize:: option for the server from the default 128MB.
::

classmethods::

method::ar

argument::in
The input sound

argument::pitchRatio
The pitch shift ratio. For safety, values are clipped between 0.01 and 64.

argument::formantRatio
The formant shift ratio. The default is 0.0, which means that the pitch shifter
will automatically calculate the formant shift for formant preservation.
For safety, unless the strong::formantRatio:: is 0.0, the value will be clipped between 0.01 and 64.

argument::mul
An amount by which to multiply the output signal

argument::add
An amount to add to the output signal

Examples::

A basic example
code::
{
	var sig = Saw.ar(440, 1.0);
	sig = RubberBandPS.ar(sig, 0.5, 0.5);
}.play;
::

An example that shows the latency
code::
{
	var sig, shift;
	sig = Saw.ar(440, 1.0);
	shift = RubberBandPS.ar(sig, 0.5, 0.5);
	sig = sig * Env.perc(0.01, 0.3).ar;
	shift = shift * Env.perc(0.01, 0.3).ar;
	sig + shift
}.play;
::